{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_bison_ver01/data/sn83045217/00295860728/1921031001/0769.xml":{"full_text":"Olsen Feels Finer\nhan for 25 Years\nI\nSalt Lake Man Says He Feels\nLike Brand New Person\nSince Taking Tanlac.\n\"It's a fact I looked for the right\nmedicine for 25 years and found it at\nlast in this Tanlac,\" said John A.\nOlsen, Wk East Seventh south. Salt\nLake City, cabinet maker with the\nModern Furniture Co.\n\"I had stomach trouble in a bad form\nand then I was takon with the rheu\nmatism. Between the two of them I\nhave had a hard time for the past 25\nyears. Nothing I ate agreed with me\nand my legs nearly always hurt me so\nbad I just had to hobble around. I got\nManufacture, Sale of Beer,\nWines, Liquors for Sickly\nPermi ssible, Is New Ruling\nOpinion, Rendered by Palmer March 3, States\nAmount for Nonbeverage Purposes\nMust Not Be Limited.\nWashington, March 9.\u2014The governmtnt is without author\nity to prohibit the manufacture and sales of liquor, wines or\nbeer for non-beverage purposes, according to a ruling made by\nthe attorney general and published Wednesday by the internal\nrevenue bureau.\nThe opinion, one of the most com\nprehensive dealing with the question of\nprohibition, expressly states that there\nmust be no limitation on the use of\nliquors for nonbeverage purposes ex\ncept that prescribed by congress in\nlimiting the sale of spiritous liquors\nto one pint for 10 days. The question\nof limitation, the opinion said, thus is\nleft to the good faith of the physician.\nLimitation Removed.\n\"Subject to this limitation,\" the\nopinion continued, \"obviously there has\nbeen committed not to the judgment\nof the commissioner of internal reve\nnue and the secretary of the treasury,\nbut for the professional judgment of\nthe physician, the question of the quan\ntity of liquor that may be used to ad\nvantage as a medicine in each case.\n\"As to this question, I think the in\ntention was to leave the physician un\nfettered by governmental control, but\nsubject to be dealt with criminally and\nby revocation of his permit if he acts\nin bad faith.\"\nPermits Restriction Off.\nThe opinion, existence of which be\ncame known Sunday, was signed by the\nthen Attorney General Palmer and was\ndated March 3.\nMr. Palmer also held that the gov\nWilson 9 s 150 Million Fund\nReport Forthcoming in\n3 Months, Says Treasury\nBarney Baruch, Who Was Technical Adviser,\nPaid $150,000 by Ex-President for\nPersonal Expenses.\nWashington, March 0.\u2014It will re\nquire at least three months for the\ntreasury department to submit an item\nized statement showing: detailed expen\nditures under the $150,000,000 special\nwar fund set aside for use by the presi\ndent. Such a statement was called for\nin a resolution adopted two weeks ago\nby the house.\nIn the report transmitted by Presi\ndent Wilson, previous to adjournment\nof congress, and made public Wednes\nday, total net disbursements were\n8114,907,<70. It was stated that there\nwas an unallotted balance of about\n$12,000,000 and that approximately\n$23,000,000 had been carried to sur\nplus fund.\nThe president sent to the house a\nletter from the secretary of the\ntreasury saying:\n\"Im view of the fact that the dis\nbursements rep'esent for the most\npart advances of funds for disbursing\nofficers upon accountable warrants, it\ncannot be said that the figures are final\nor that they necessarily represent ac\ntual expenditures. The auditor for the\nstate and other departments who ex\namines the accounts of the disbursing\nofficers concerned advises that it will\nStarving Austria\nMust Give Milch\nCows to Allies\nVienna, March 9\u2014Formal notice\nthat it would be required to fulfill\nthe livestock provisions of the\ntreaty of St. Germain was served\nupon the Austrian government by\nthe reparations commission Tues\nday. This involves delivery to\nItaly. Jugo-Slavia and Rumania\nof 20,000 head of cattle, including\n6.000 milch cows.\nThe American representatives in\nthe reparations body, before their\nwithdrawal, had, together with the\nBritish opposed such action on\nthe ground that it was unfair to\nthe countries which are supplying\nAustria with quantities of milk\nand fats and that the nations to\nwhich the cattle would go did not\nactually need the stock.\nThis Woman Suffered.\nMrs. II. A. Leaman, Sturgin, Colo.,\nwrites: \"I suffered with bladder and\nkidney trouble for years. Doctored\nand tried everything. No help. Final\nly a friend sent me Foley Kidney Pills.\nThey helped me so much I used 7 bot\ntles. Now I feel fine. Spent sleep\nless nights. Suffered so it seemed I\nhardly could live. Recommend Foley\nKidney Ifells to all who suffer from\nkidney trouble as I did.\" Great Falls\nDrus Co.\u2014 Adr.\nso I slept very little and in the morn\ning would feel all frazzled out. I was\ndiscouraged because I tried many dif\nferent medicines but they did me no\nmore good than so much water.\n\"It was a lucky day for me when I\nstarted on Tanlac, because that proved\nto be what I had been needing all along.\nMy only regret is I didn't get it years\nago. It just made me feel like a new\nman. My stomach is in first class con\ndition and I haven't a sign of rheuma\ntism. I don't even have headaches like\nI used to. Tanlac did a thorough job\nfor me and made me feel better and\nstronger than I have for 25 years. It\ncertainly is a wonder.\"\nTanlac is sold in Great Falls by\nModel lis Pharmacy, 312 Central ave\nnue, and Cascade Rx Pharmacy, 110\nThird street south.\u2014Adv.\nernmeiit was without authority to lim\nit the number of permits to manufac\nture or sell wine in any state or lo\ncality.\n\"I cannot believe,\" lie said, \"that it\nwas the intention that the executive\noffices should have anything to say\nthat one reputable druggist in a com\nmunity should have a permit and an\nother equally reputable should not.\"\nRevenue Ruling Conflicts.\nInternal revenue officers are con\nsidering removal of the ban prohibit\ning withdrawals of liquor from ware\nhouses, Commissioner Williams said\nWednesday. The order was issued last\nDecember to permit wholesal/ liquor\ndealers to dispose of their stocks on\nhand and Mr. Williams said he be\nlieved that the purpose of the order\nvirtually had been accomplished.\nThe decision of revenue and prohi\nbition officials not to grant permits\nto wholesale dealers hereafter, putting\nan end to their business, will stand,\naccording to Mr. Williams, who added\nthat there was no reason for a third\nparty to engage in the handling of\nliquor. The law provides that the re\ntail druggist may purchase direct from\nthe warehouses and on that basis he\nbelieved the decision of the enforce\nment officials should stand.\ntake about three months to complete\nthe examination.\"\nMuch of the fund allotted to the state\ndepartment was for use in Russia, in\ncluding $5,000,000 for the civilian pop\nulation in the Archangel district and\n$4,500,000 for operation and mainte\nnance of the trans-Siberian and Chinese\nEastern railways.\n15. M. Baruch. a technical adviser to\nthe peace mission, was allotted $150,\n000 for expenses.\nThe shipping board was allotted $27,\n000,000 for purchase and repair of\nGerman and Austrian vessels.\n(o/etv&ro -E ight\nOn Exhibit at the\nAUTOMOBILE SHOW\nNext Week\nGREAT FALLS AUTO\nTRUCK CO.\nPhone 6048\u2014305 1st Ave. No.\nColi Motoo Cap Oywvjwwwiiioui. USA.\nik.\niSSLm\ni/Aerms a okueK c/~ JBmorro*'\ntn irfU CoU Do*\u00bb Oodby\nA\nCATARRHAL JELLY.\nFOR\nColds\n>va\u00ae\n,\\:ul\noA\n_ Get m tub\u00ab to*\no>y. M\u00abk\u00abi your\nhead and not\u00ab\n(\u2022\u2022I fin\u00ab.\nEasy to apply\n\u00abQuick to act\n20 treatment tin FREE\u2014Writ*\nKONDON MFG. CO.\nMinncapolia. Minn.\nSHELLS FROM BALTIC\nFLEET START PANIC\nAM ONG RED TR OOPS\nCommunist Garrison at Oranienbaum Deserts to\nRevolutionaries After Shooting All Regimen\ntal Commissaries and Capturing Ice Breakers\nBetween Capital and Kronstadt Fortress.\nLondon, March 9.\u2014Another version of the situation in\nPetrograd is given in a Central News dispatch from Helsing\nfors dated Wednesday. This says that fighting is continuing\nin the streets of Petrograd and that War Minister Trotzky and\nand M. Zinovieff, chief of the soviet government of Petrograd,\nwere reported to have taken refuge in the fortress of St. Peter\nand St. Paul, surrounded by a large number of protective troops.\nAll attempts by the revolutionaries to capture this fortress\nwere repulsed, the message says.\nShips\nAid Revolters.\nShips of the Baltic participated in\nbombardment of Petrograd, says a\nRiga dispatch to the London Times. A\npanic ensued among the red troops\nand communists. The garrison at Or\nandenbaum deserted to the revolution\naries after shooting all regimental com\nmissaries and communists and also\ncaptured two ice breakers between Pe\ntrograd and Kronstadt.\nCommunication between Russia and\nSiberia has been cut for more than a\nfortnight says an official wireless mes\nsage from Moscow today. The break\nis ascribed to the work of social revo\nlutionaries operating with generals\nformerly attached to the forces of the\nlate Admiral Kolefiakl the message\nadds.\nRUSSIAN SITUATION IS\nCONFLICTING\u2014COPENHAGEN\nCopenhagen, March 9\u2014(By The As\nsociated Press).\u2014News of the Rus\nsian situation Wednesday was conflict\ning with the latest Helsingfors dis\npatches rei>orting that the soviet gov\nernment forces had recaptured the for\ntresses of Krasnoya Gorko and Sys\nterbak Wednesday morning and were\ntraining the big guns upon Kronstadt,\nwhere fires were observed.\nAn infantry assault by the soviet\ntroops upon Kronstadt is reported to\nhave been repulsed with enormous\nlosses to the attacking forces.\nSoviet Troops in Suburbs.\nThese reports were preceded by\nclaims made in Helsingfors dispatches\nthat Petrograd was in the hands of the\nrevolutionaries. According to a Reval\nmessage, however, the soviet troops\nrecaptured the southeastern suburbs of\nPetrograd.\nThousands of. fugitives from Petro\ngrad are clamoring for entry into r in\nland, the Finnish advices state.\nWHITE RUTHENIANS\nPROCLAIM FREEDOM\nWarsaw. March 9\u2014(By The Associ\nated Press).\u2014The white Ruthenians\nhave proclaimed their independence\nfrom Russia, according to a Minsk re\nport received here Wednesday.\n(The Ituthenians meant probably are\nthose inhabiting what is known as\nwhite Russia, comprising the south\nwestern Iiussiau provinces, centering\nupon Minsk.)\nCOMMUNIST WORKERS\nINDIGNANT, SAYS TROTZKY\nLondon, March 9.\u2014Workers in sov\niet Russia are indignant over the revo\nlutionary uprising at Kronstadt and\nare beginning to be allowed to fight\nagainst the forces engaged with soviet\ntroops there, says a wireless dispatch\nfrom Moscow. It is said in the dis\npatch that \"friction is beginning to be\nnoticeable among the mutineers.\"\nThe tenth congress of the Russian\ncommunist party opened at Moscow\nTuesday under difficult circumstances,\nthe dispatch said.\n\"The republic is surrounded by an\nendless number of enemies,\" it con\ntinues. \"The short breathing space\ngiven Russia has been interrupted by\nnew entente intrigues. The tasks con\n-er\n\nCuticura For All\nSkin Irritations\nBathe with Cuticura Soap and hot water\nto free the pores of impurities and follow\nwith a gentle application of Cuticura Oint\nment to soothe and heal. They are ideal\nfor the toilet, as is also Cuticura Talcum\nfor perfuming.\ntaptalukTmVrlUll. AiUrai: \"Qcttmrt LaV\n\u2022r.tariM. 30, 48, MaM.\" SoMeverr\nwhen. Soap Sc. Ointmat2SandiOe. TalenmSe.\nMTC aticu Soap ibim without mua.\nA\nspinn\nYou must say \"Bayer\"\nUnless you see the name Bayer' on package\nor on tablets, you are not getting genuine\nAspirin prescribed by physicians for 21 years.\nInsist upon an unbroken package of genuine\n\"Bayer Tablets of Aspirin\" containing proper\ndirections and dose proved safe by millions.\nHandy tin box\u00ab* of 12 tablet\u00ab \u00a